  "doc_id": "38010",
  "text": "Several studies have evaluated the spread of cold in lower limbs. Mars et al. [CITATION_1] compared the cooling of skin, subcutaneous fat, and muscle produced by an icepack while at rest and after short-duration exhaustive exercise. They have shown that the reductions in temperature were significant in the control limbs and the exercised limbs. Thanks to a thermocouple, they proved that cold continues to spread for 15 min after installing a cold pack. They also found a significant decrease in skin temperatures. For certain authors, this decrease is dependent on the subcutaneous fat rate and on the delay of the sympathetic nervous system activation [CITATION_2] . Cryotherapy also reduces blood flow and muscle metabolism, even after the removal of the cryogenic source, as shown by Ho et al. [CITATION_3] . Thorsson et al. [11] studied the effect of local cold application on intramuscular blood flow at rest and after running in eight male distance runners, where one leg was cooled for 20 min by applying two instant cold packs on the quadriceps muscle. They measured a reduction in blood flow compared to the control leg by up to 49%.",
